  "Net force is the vector sum of all forces acting on an object. Forces in the same direction add together, while forces in opposite directions subtract. The net force determines the object's acceleration.": "",
  "If two forces act on an object in the same direction, how do you find the net force?": "",
  "Subtract the smaller from the larger force": "",
  "Add the two forces together": "",
  "Multiply the two forces together": "",
  "Divide one force by the other one": "",
  "When two forces act in the same direction, they reinforce each other. You add their magnitudes to get the net force. For example, 5 N right + 3 N right = 8 N right.": "",
  "If two forces act in opposite directions, how do you find the net force?": "",
  "Add their magnitudes together for the total": "",
  "Multiply their magnitudes together for total": "",
  "Divide the larger by the smaller force value": "",
  "When forces act in opposite directions, they partially cancel. Subtract the smaller from the larger to get the net force. The direction of the net force is the same as the larger force.": "",
